    },
    {
      "id": "3kFNf_cPqZn3zTk28i10E",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -1891.7805878853987,
      "y": 7370.498844486565,
      "width": 1351.16748046875,
      "height": 105,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#2f9e44",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffc9c9",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 2,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b63",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 2147349230,
      "version": 201,
      "versionNonce": 1107150130,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1761456522154,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Forking is a way for operating systems to create new processes by creating copies of themselves. \nWith this, you get a new process ID and a few other bits of information and handles, so \nthe newly forked process (child) can talk to the original process parent.",
      "fontSize": 28,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Forking is a way for operating systems to create new processes by creating copies of themselves. \nWith this, you get a new process ID and a few other bits of information and handles, so \nthe newly forked process (child) can talk to the original process parent.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "m30bU4fcPhk3lTDrczI4_",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -1891.1311738228987,
      "y": 6789.391056400627,
      "width": 1439.56005859375,
      "height": 105,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#2f9e44",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffc9c9",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 2,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b64",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1272905838,
      "version": 150,
      "versionNonce": 965861102,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1761456522154,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": " Forking\n        let’s discuss how we actually go about doing it in a single threaded application like Redis.how\nredis use forking and copy-on-write ",
      "fontSize": 28,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": " Forking\n        let’s discuss how we actually go about doing it in a single threaded application like Redis.how redis use forking and copy-on-write ",
      "autoResize": false,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "qQ2O3DZTj0BzuV_t9c7Pr",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -1889.230132156232,
      "y": 7513.334741296461,
      "width": 1571.443115234375,
      "height": 420,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#2f9e44",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffc9c9",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 2,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b65",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1772195502,
      "version": 501,
      "versionNonce": 1211256562,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1761456522154,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Now here is where things get interesting. Redis is a process with tons of memory allocated to it, \nso how does it make a copy without running out of memory?\nWhen you fork a process, the parent and child share memory,\n and in that child process Redis begins the snapshotting (Redis) process. This is made possible \nby a memory sharing technique called copy-on-write —which passes references to the memory at the \ntime the fork was created. If no changes occur while the child process is\n persisting to disk, no new allocations are made.\n\nIn the case where there are changes, the kernel keeps track of references to each page, and if there are more \nthan one to specific page the changes are written to new pages. The child process is fully unaware of the change \nand has consistent memory snapshot. Therefore only fraction of the memory is used and we are able to achieve a \npoint in time snapshot of potentially gigabytes of memory extremely quickly and efficiently!",
      "fontSize": 28,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Now here is where things get interesting. Redis is a process with tons of memory allocated to it, \nso how does it make a copy without running out of memory?\nWhen you fork a process, the parent and child share memory,\n and in that child process Redis begins the snapshotting (Redis) process. This is made possible \nby a memory sharing technique called copy-on-write —which passes references to the memory at the \ntime the fork was created. If no changes occur while the child process is\n persisting to disk, no new allocations are made.\n\nIn the case where there are changes, the kernel keeps track of references to each page, and if there are more \nthan one to specific page the changes are written to new pages. The child process is fully unaware of the change \nand has consistent memory snapshot. Therefore only fraction of the memory is used and we are able to achieve a \npoint in time snapshot of potentially gigabytes of memory extremely quickly and efficiently!",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "gczP2Oimp_7kg-ibmwPib",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -2023.0286347603999,
      "y": 5627.259179773025,
      "width": 475.19970703125,
      "height": 90,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#2f9e44",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffc9c9",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 2,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b67",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1009349102,
